,Not Recommended,252550,32701188,Posted: 23 June,all,quaternary,"Very slow movement speed, ""puzzles"" based on parkour and dexterity rather than actual thinking (and no quicksaving, so if you fail you're set back about five minutes), and puzzles based on finding hidden objects rather than actual thinking.The game does a poor job at communicating the puzzles to players:* Very unclear connections, SO MANY ""mystery buttons"".* You can look on the ground (sometimes) for connections leading into devices, but they don't change color when the device is activated (like an antline in Portal), so it's hard to tell whether the button is actually pressed. They're also nearly the same color as the walls and floors anyways, so you really have to squint to follow them.* It doesn't help that the game intentionally hides buttons.* ...as well as the cubes you require to solve them. It's possible to look at a puzzle, find it to be impossible, but then look in a random crevice you didn't think to look into before and find like fifteen red cubes that would have trivialized the puzzle.* A number of puzzles have BLATANT unintended solutions.* A number of puzzles don't even use anywhere close to all the cubes.* Buttons look exactly the same as a completely different puzzle element (red cubes)* World 2 is very dark for no discernible reason. I could hardly see what I am supposed to do.* Because there's no quicksaving, few checkpoints, and very very long screen transitions (why?), it's really hard to justify experimentation in the puzzles.Breaks a number of like, Puzzle Design 101 things:* Red herrings.* Trapping situations.* Hiding stuff.* Execution-based puzzles.* Experimentation discouraged.* No difficulty curve - the harder levels are hard because they have more parkour and hidden objects, not more thinking.Took a look at the level editor.* It's a grid/voxel based game, but nothing snaps to the grid by default?* Doors have the complete wrong origin - if you use grid snap on them they either hover half a unit above the ground or sink half a unit below it.* Very hard to sketch out puzzles with the ease of something like Portal 2's Puzzlemaker. It takes forever to even get a room set up, never mind an actual puzzle. Controls are very clunky."
