76561197969417125,Recommended,252550,24921830,"Posted: 14 August, 2016",all,G00N3R,"Qbeh is a first person puzzle game where the player must progress through a series of temple style structures that are built out of cubes, and are floating amongst the clouds. I really enjoyed playing Qbeh. Its a shame that it didn't get a lot of media attention, and consequently I guess not many people have played it, because I think its much better than certain other games that gained a lot more hype *cough*thewitness*cough*.The main objective of each level is simply to enter the portal to travel to the next level. The problem is, each level is filled with ledges that are too high to climb, and gaps in the floor that are too long to jump across. Fortunately, scattered around each level are coloured blocks that you can collect and place in specific locations to help you reach your goal. Each type of block is useful in different ways. Red blocks just exist to stand on, blues can unlock doors and power moving platforms, purples create a field of low gravity and greens can move either horizontally or vertically but disappear after a few seconds.The level design is really intelligent, especially later in the game, when you're using multiple different blocks together, and you encounter additional hazards, such as fans that can push you off a ledge, and a black ooze covering the walls and floor that kills you instantly if you touch it. Many areas feel like they've got multiple solutions. Every level also has a glowing prism hidden away in a secret location. Finding these usually requires thorough exploration, and creative block usage. But they also give you that really satisfying ""I am the smartest person in the world"" feeling.I've finished all the main levels and found half the secrets, in just under 9 hours. There are a few more bonus levels but they're unlocked by finding all the secrets, which is something that only the most dedicated players will do. I didn't encounter any bugs or crashes and the controls are fully rebindable. I also have to say the music is great, and it creates a relaxing, chilled out mood.The only real negative I can mention is the lack of a story tying all the levels together. It kind of feels like we're exploring the ruins of a dead civilisation, so it would have been cool to know more.If you enjoy first person puzzle games such as Portal, Talos Principle or Qube, I highly recommend Qbeh. I'd say its worth a full price purchase, but at least give it a try on a sale."
76561198044953223,Recommended,252550,18079315,"Posted: 17 September, 2015",all,Axolian,"With the level editor FINALLY being implemented after so long, I can definitely recommend this game.Even with the base content, it's definitely worth the $9.99 USD price tag. There are a total of 36 levels spread out around 6 'worlds', each with their own theme such as spring, winter, fall, summer, etc. Each level has a secret, which is a golden triangle, and if you manage to find all of them in worlds 1-5, world 6 will then unlock. In addition, there are a few extra secrets for achievements as well.The gameplay is typical of puzzlers, starting out easy and getting progressively harder. However, it is also VERY fun, with four (technically five, but the fifth is a portal key to unlock the next world only found in the last level for each world) block types. The red cube, which is a structure block. The blue cube, which is a power block. The purple cube, which is a cube that reduces gravity in a certain range. And the green cube, which is a motor device that deteriorates after a certain distance. Typically, each world introduces a new block type, making the levels and designs more and more complex and challenging. Expect to fall out of the world to your death many times, this can be a very challenging puzzler.The sounds and music are also superb. Each level has its own special music track, each as equally entrancing as the last. The musical score for this game is honestly amazing, and they also have the soundtrack available for purchase, which I will provide the link to(https://launchablesocks.bandcamp.com/album/qbeh-1-ost).I can't leave out the graphics. For as simple as this game is, the visuals are honestly breathtaking. Lighting and shadowing are definitely the biggest strong points of this game graphically, and they never disappoint. Everything from the soft lighting on the blocks, the varying skyboxes, the flowing trees, and the glistening water all look the very best. If you're a sucker for that kind of thing, you might find yourself like I was, anticipating the next levels to see what lighting and graphics tricks they would apply next.The only thing that's really any kind of drawback is the lack of a story whatsoever. There isn't necessarily an obvious point to the puzzling madness, but imo it's nothing major. It isn't what the selling point is anyway in any case.Amazing game, definitely a must-buy for puzzle fans, particularly if it's ever on sale, and I'm very excited to play and build community levels."
