,Recommended,252550,10420460,"Posted: 10 June, 2014",all,goodwithcomputr,"The experience, though obviously inspired by other first-person puzzle games, feels entirely new. It does the impossible: marrying relaxation with puzzles, without making those puzzles childishly simple.Though the game relies on a relatively small pallet of environmental and graphical elements, it introduces them gradually enough that it continuously warrants (and rewards) those who like to explore, and especially those whose curiosity takes them outside the boundaries of the ""normal"" level path. Qbeh-1's difficulty ramps up considerably should you choose to search for its secrets. Though they're not essential, they do unlock extra levels, and the complex puzzles you must solve in order to find these secrets make them a reward in and of themselves. With or without the secrets, however, the difficulty level will increase as you reach the middle and end of the game; you are eased gently into this world, without feeling as though you're drudging through a tutorial. Once you learn the basics and begin craving more exploration, new elements (like gravity-defying jumps!) make your progress worthwhile and your journey fulfilling.As in Antichamber, Perspective, The Bridge, and other great puzzle titles, the narrative is merely implied, and never treated to full exposition. I happen to love ambiguous stories, and if you feel the same way you'll find it very rewarding to piece the game's limited number of clues together.Qbeh-1 is beautiful, therapeutic, and fun.4.5/5"
