,Recommended,252550,26281169,"Posted: 28 October, 2016",all,DarkGriffin,"This is a very good action puzzle game, and easily worth the price with or without a sale.What really surprised me was the amount of ""skill layers"" the game has.  First you will be finishing levels, finding that quite hard enough.  By the end of the 5 worlds, you'll be ready to go back and start spotting secrets, sort of a ""level 2"" of the whole game.  It's all quite a nice learning curve and builds up on previous game skills and your newfound knowledge of using the game elements together.The base game with the first credits ending can be obtained within 6-8 hours.  But if you are the curious sort and are running without looking at the guides, the secrets and hidden stuff can easily bring that total to 20 hours as you unlock more hidden stuff.  I don't want to spoil it in this review, but the game has a little bit more to it then first appears.It's gameplay focuses most on physical placement puzzles, but you will need to practice some platforming to complete it.  Especally at the end, there are a few points where you will need to be quick at placing or grabbing blocks.  Nothing too insane, most of the ""action sequences"" are either straightforward or you will be given a chance to oversee the area before diving into it.  The speed parts are more a test of your ability to stay calm and stick to a previously thought up plan under pressure then anything else.  Checkpoints are quite plenty as well, and instantly reload if you fall or die.The levels are brillantly laid out.  You often will find what you need with a little bit of exploring.  In the process of finding those bricks you also will have a good visual of each new puzzle you come across before needing to solve it.  There are also lots of hidden and not so hidden places that are simply eye candy or ""breathing space"", so you really do feel like you are exploring instead of walking from puzzle to puzzle.  A few have some great views or other neat little rewards for being curious.  Some (but not all) of the puzzles also have many solutions, leaving it up to you to ""free solve"" it several different ways.  I loved the ""smart"" feeling I got for coming up with solutions that didn't use all the blocks or let me walk out with extra ones for the next area.The music is also very good, and passes in and out throughout the levels to aid in creating some pretty neat moods and situations.  It's very cool how each level has almost the same level elements but each also has a very unique feel or mood to match the puzzle themes.  It will keep you pumped for the big puzzles, and stay quiet when you need silence to focus or transition your mind between puzzles.On the negative, some levels loading times were a bit long on my low end computer.  The checkpoints respawning is very fast, which is very welcome when you fall off and it auto reloads nearly instantly.  The game only needs to load the level when you first enter it or transition to a new one from a level exit.  So it's nothing game breaking.One other thing to note is that while the levels have lots of checkpoints to them, each level can take anywhere from 15 to 45 minuites the first time you explore it.  If you quit the game you will lose your checkpoint and have to start at the very beginning of the level again.  It's not terrible as once you know the solutions each puzzle can be ""redone"" in under a minute tops.  But it's worth noting this isn't a quick pop in and out type of game.I highly recommend this one if you like physical/positional puzzles.  It's a great experience that manages to be so much more then it's parts, thanks to very clever level design and careful use of music and level name tags.  It doesn't try to overreach or do something it can't do, like having a dialog story or being a hardcore difficulty suddenly.  Every time it reaches the point of feeling impossible the level design steps back a notch and shifts gears, keeping it fresh till the end.I had gone in expecting a small little game about placing blocks that would last 6-8 hours tops and probably rip off minecraft.  Having played Qbeh, I can say I certainly recieved much more then that.  This experience is going to stick with me as a personal favorite for quite some time."
,Recommended,252550,26804136,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,DSpecht,"Qbeh-1 perfectly achieves what it sets out to do: Being an atmospheric puzzle game. Nothing more, nothing less.The ambience the game sets is incredible. A soothing soundtrack, mysterious ruins and mellow light effects all do their part to pull the player into the level. The puzzles in Qbeh-1 are easy enough to keep the immersion of the overall setting, but also challenging enough to not be boring. Hidden secrets and the occasional easter egg reward exploring.Qbeh-1 offers 36 levels and supports Community Created levels for additional fun.If you enjoy exploration, a relaxing and sometimes breathtaking ambience or decently crafted puzzles Qbeh-1 is 	definitely worth buying."
